    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The cost, in dollars, to produce <m>x</m>
          <q>I'd rather be a Sasquatch</q>
          T-Shirts is <m>C(x) = 2x+26</m>,
          <m>x \geq 0</m> and the price-demand function,
          in dollars per shirt, is <m>p(x) = 30 - 2x</m>, <m>0 \leq x \leq 15</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>C(0) = 26</m>, so the fixed costs are <m>\dollar26</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\overline{C}(10) = 4.6</m>,
              so when 10 shirts are produced,
              the cost per shirt is <m>\dollar4.60</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>p(5) = 20</m>, so to sell <m>5</m> shirts,
              set the price at <m>\dollar20</m> per shirt.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>R(x) = -2x^2+30x</m>, <m>0 \leq x \leq 15</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>P(x) = -2x^2+28x-26</m>, <m>0 \leq x \leq 15</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>P(x) = 0</m> when <m>x = 1</m> and <m>x=13</m>.
              These are the <q>break even</q> points,
              so selling <m>1</m> shirt or <m>13</m> shirts will guarantee the revenue earned exactly recoups the cost of production.
