      </statement>
      <answer>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>C(0) = 1000</m>, so the monthly fixed costs are <m>1000</m>
              <em>hundred</em> dollars,
              or <m>\dollar100,\!000</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\overline{C}(10) = 120</m>,
              so when 10 scooters are made,
              the cost per scooter is <m>120</m> hundred dollars,
              or <m>\dollar12,\!000</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>p(5) = 130</m>, so to sell <m>5</m> scooters a month,
              set the price at <m>130</m> hundred dollars,
              or <m>\dollar13,\!000</m> per scooter.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>R(x) = -2x^2+140x</m>, <m>0 \leq x \leq 70</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>P(x) = -2x^2+120x-1000</m>, <m>0 \leq x \leq 70</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>P(x) = 0</m> when <m>x = 10</m> and <m>x=50</m>.
              These are the <q>break even</q> points,
              so selling <m>10</m> scooters or <m>50</m> scooters a month will guarantee the revenue earned exactly recoups the cost of production.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <p>
